      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You raise a very strong point; the tendency toward \"us vs. them\" is a recurring feature across many nationalist iterations. It suggests that nationalism, regardless of its framing, inherently creates boundaries that can breed animosity toward outsiders. In a highly interconnected, globalized world, a purely nationalistic approach presents considerable friction with international cooperation and diverse perspectives. Perhaps the necessary political shift lies in prioritizing supranational identities or cosmopolitanism over exclusive national loyalties.",
      "source": "target",
